title: Fix kernel registry validation to reenable DML kernels
body:
This fixes a regression introduced in PR 2137, which caused some DML kernel registrations to be ignored, affecting performance by causing fallback to CPU.  

The issue was ORT stopped accepting kernel registrations that it thought were duplicate.  DML registrations were incorrectly flagged as duplicate because the validation logic didn't correctly handle the case of maximum version of INT_MAX.  

The DML EP and Winml's custom op ABI use INT_MAX to express that the maximum version should be inferred from schema registrations (see VerifyKernelDef).  Since schema registrations aren't always available at the point that kernels are registered, the fix makes ORT make conservative assumptions during validation.

This removes a temporary workaround for the duplicate registrations in the DML EP.  That workaround wasn't correctly adding values to a map, leading to missing optimization.

title: Spawn child process to run DeviceLostRecovery scenario test
body:
DeviceLostRecovery scenario test needs to have a clean environment in which previous tests cannot reference the d3d12 device so that the removal of references in line 1457 will be successful.

By using "EXPECT_EXIT" which is a Google Death Test, the test will be spawned in a child process using CreateProcess and "exit(0)" is added at the end of the test code to indicate that the test has suceeded. EXPECT_EXIT will expect that the child process exited with code 0.

According to Google Test guidelines, it is recommended to add "DeathTest" to the test suite name because test suites with a name ending in "DeathTest" are run before all other tests.

title: Fix custom ops scenario tests
body:
Custom ops scenario tests needed to create the adapter for usage of "GetCustomRegistry".

As a result, lotus environment would be created and WinMLAdapter would be destructed and lotus environment would be destructed in which the Ort::Environment is destructed and ::google::protobuf::ShutdownProtobufLibrary is called. This doesn't work for the scenario in which and Ort::Environment is destructed and recreated.

This change also "lazy loads" lotus environment so that it's not in the WinMLAdapter constructor but in the first place that requries usage of it: OverrideSchemaInferenceFunctions. This is used in creating a LearningModel in the LearningModel constructor.

title: remove references to dxcore related attributes when building redist package
body:
the winml redist package will be built on agent pools without the latest prerelease sdk that contains the new Dxcore APIs. Therefore, currently this release pipeline fails because it cannot recognize references to D3D_FEATURE_LEVEL_1_0_CORE. To fix this we need to ifdef out references to these APIs when building redist. The assumption here is that redist customers will not expect prerelease features to be available.

References to Dxcore have already been handled at preprocessor time in WinML, this PR addresses DML EP.

title: Windowsai
body:
This PR is for comment on bringing the newly layered Windows ML components into the master branch for the ONNX runtime for windows.

This is anticipation of a beta release of these bits over the next couple of months.    We will include more documentation on how to use , how the layers work, and the relationships of WinML and ORT and DML (which we introduced to master in ORT v1.0) .

Most likely we will not merge this PR to master until after the holidays due to US vacation schedules and such but we want to get the PR posted for comment by the community and the ORT developer base.

Some of the things we have done in this PR:

- Added a top level directory "/winml"
- Contributed all of the windows inbox code from the Windows.AI.MachineLearning namespace into that directory .  Making it available using the MIT license.
- Started a layering effort to have the new Windows.AI.MachineLearning.dll consume the onnxruntime.dll c_abi that we introduced in v1.0 .
- Added an "adapter" module that gets linked into the core onnxruntime.dll.  This adapter is private to the WinML component, and provides ABI functionality required for the layering effort.  this is *not*  a new public ABI and is not support for developer to call.
- made the WinML ABI fully available for public developers to call.    
- You can now include both of these DLL's (WinML + ORT) in your projects that want to use the WinML ABI as a redist component.
- added cmakery for all of this work.  There is now a "use_winml" build flag in addition to the "use_dml" build flag
- added google test unit tests for the newly added WinML ABI.  these are under the top level "winml/test" folder.
- and several other things :)

Enjoy !
